          <h3>Business fundamentals</h3>
            <p>What the business do?</p>
            <p><b>Has the company a healthy corporate culture?</b> From my perspective, the company´s employees are critical for the success (or the fail) of the company, so look for signs, reports, articles about the company´s culture.</p>
            <p>Which are the competitors of the business?</p>
            <p>Which is the market share of the company?</p>
            <p><b>Is the management of the company keeping its promises?</b> Take one of the earnings calls from previous quarters, and listen carefully what the management said. Then analyze if they kept its promises</p>


          <h3>Financial overview</h3>
            <p><b>Is a profitable company?</b> Good examples: PayPal (company) ($PYPL), Alibaba (online company) ($BABA), NVIDIA ($NVDA)</p>
            <p><b>Is the stock expensive?</b> Look for P/E ratio, PEG ration, EPS, Enterprise Value to Free Cash Flow ratio, Price to Free Cash Flow ratio, etc.</p>
            <p>Is the company generating so much cash flow to support growth of the business? Research closely the balance sheet of the company in the last year and last 3 quarter reports, especially the cash flow statements. Forget about net income; the real deal here are the,cash and cash equivalents for the period, operating cash flow and Free Cash Flow</p>
            <p><b>Is the company a serial acquirer?</b> If this is the case, make your own research how the company has integrated its new assets to the overall strategy and long term mission of the organization. One of my favorite examples here are Salesforce.com (company) ($CRM)</p>
            <p>Is its <b>Debt/Equity ratio</b> healthy?</p>
            <p>Is its <b>Long Term Debt to Total Assets Ratio</b> healthy?</p>




